README.md
     9в†’# Mitt
    11в†’> Tiny 200b functional event emitter / pubsub.
    12в†’
    13в†’-   **Microscopic:** weighs less than 200 bytes gzipped
    14в†’-   **Useful:** a wildcard `"*"` event type listens to all events
    15в†’-   **Familiar:** same names & ideas as [Node's EventEmitter](https://nodejs.org/api/events.html#events_class_eventemitter)
    16в†’-   **Functional:** methods don't rely on `this`
    17в†’-   **Great Name:** somehow [mitt](https://npm.im/mitt) wasn't taken
    18в†’
    19в†’Mitt was made for the browser, but works in any JavaScript runtime. It has no dependencies and supports IE9+.
    20в†’
    21в†’## Table of Contents
    23в†’-   [Install](#install)
    24в†’-   [Usage](#usage)
    25в†’-   [Examples & Demos](#examples--demos)
    26в†’-   [API](#api)
    27в†’-   [Contribute](#contribute)
    28в†’-   [License](#license)
    29в†’
    30в†’## Install
    32в†’This project uses [node](http://nodejs.org) and [npm](https://npmjs.com). Go check them out if you don't have them locally installed.
    33в†’
    34в†’```sh
    35в†’$ npm install --save mitt
    36в†’```
    37в†’
    38в†’Then with a module bundler like [rollup](http://rollupjs.org/) or [webpack](https://webpack.js.org/), use as you would anything else:
    39в†’
    40в†’```javascript
    41в†’// using ES6 modules
    42в†’import mitt from 'mitt'
    43в†’
    44в†’// using CommonJS modules
    45в†’var mitt = require('mitt')
    46в†’```
    47в†’
    48в†’The [UMD](https://github.com/umdjs/umd) build is also available on [unpkg](https://unpkg.com):
    49в†’
    50в†’```html
    51в†’<script src="https://unpkg.com/mitt/dist/mitt.umd.js"></script>
    52в†’```
    53в†’
    54в†’You can find the library on `window.mitt`.
    55в†’
    56в†’## Usage
    58в†’```js
    59в†’import mitt from 'mitt'
    60в†’
    61в†’const emitter = mitt()
    62в†’
    63в†’// listen to an event
    64в†’emitter.on('foo', e => console.log('foo', e) )
    65в†’
    66в†’// listen to all events
    67в†’emitter.on('*', (type, e) => console.log(type, e) )
    68в†’
    69в†’// fire an event
    70в†’emitter.emit('foo', { a: 'b' })
    71в†’
    72в†’// clearing all events
    73в†’emitter.all.clear()
    74в†’
    75в†’// working with handler references:
    76в†’function onFoo() {}
    77в†’emitter.on('foo', onFoo)   // listen
    78в†’emitter.off('foo', onFoo)  // unlisten
    79в†’```
    80в†’
    81в†’### Typescript
    83в†’Set `"strict": true` in your tsconfig.json to get improved type inference for `mitt` instance methods.
    84в†’
    85в†’```ts
    86в†’import mitt from 'mitt';
    87в†’
    88в†’type Events = {
    89в†’  foo: string;
    90в†’  bar?: number;
    91в†’};
    92в†’
    93в†’const emitter = mitt<Events>(); // inferred as Emitter<Events>
    94в†’
    95в†’emitter.on('foo', (e) => {}); // 'e' has inferred type 'string'
    96в†’
    97в†’emitter.emit('foo', 42); // Error: Argument of type 'number' is not assignable to parameter of type 'string'. (2345)
    98в†’```
    99в†’
   100в†’Alternatively, you can use the provided `Emitter` type:
   101в†’
   102в†’```ts
   103в†’import mitt, { Emitter } from 'mitt';
   104в†’
   105в†’type Events = {
   106в†’  foo: string;
   107в†’  bar?: number;
   108в†’};
   109в†’
   110в†’const emitter: Emitter<Events> = mitt<Events>();
   111в†’```
   112в†’
   113в†’## Examples & Demos
   123в†’## API
   127в†’#### Table of Contents
   129в†’-   [mitt](#mitt)
   130в†’-   [all](#all)
   131в†’-   [on](#on)
   132в†’    -   [Parameters](#parameters)
   133в†’-   [off](#off)
   134в†’    -   [Parameters](#parameters-1)
   135в†’-   [emit](#emit)
   136в†’    -   [Parameters](#parameters-2)
   137в†’
   138в†’### mitt
   140в†’Mitt: Tiny (~200b) functional event emitter / pubsub.
   141в†’
   142в†’Returns **Mitt** 
   143в†’
   144в†’### all
   146в†’A Map of event names to registered handler functions.
   147в†’
   148в†’### on
   150в†’Register an event handler for the given type.
   151в†’
   152в†’#### Parameters
   154в†’-   `type` **([string](https://developer.mozilla.org/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String) \| [symbol](https://developer.mozilla.org/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Symbol))** Type of event to listen for, or `'*'` for all events
   155в†’-   `handler` **[Function](https://developer.mozilla.org/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/function)** Function to call in response to given event
   156в†’
   157в†’### off
   159в†’Remove an event handler for the given type.
   160в†’If `handler` is omitted, all handlers of the given type are removed.
   161в†’
   162в†’#### Parameters
   164в†’-   `type` **([string](https://developer.mozilla.org/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String) \| [symbol](https://developer.mozilla.org/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Symbol))** Type of event to unregister `handler` from, or `'*'`
   165в†’-   `handler` **[Function](https://developer.mozilla.org/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/function)?** Handler function to remove
   166в†’
   167в†’### emit
   169в†’Invoke all handlers for the given type.
   170в†’If present, `'*'` handlers are invoked after type-matched handlers.
   171в†’
   172в†’Note: Manually firing '\*' handlers is not supported.
   173в†’
   174в†’#### Parameters
   176в†’-   `type` **([string](https://developer.mozilla.org/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String) \| [symbol](https://developer.mozilla.org/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Symbol))** The event type to invoke
   177в†’-   `evt` **Any?** Any value (object is recommended and powerful), passed to each handler
   178в†’
   179в†’## Contribute
   181в†’First off, thanks for taking the time to contribute!
   182в†’Now, take a moment to be sure your contributions make sense to everyone else.
   183в†’
   184в†’### Reporting Issues
   186в†’Found a problem? Want a new feature? First of all see if your issue or idea has [already been reported](../../issues).
   187в†’If don't, just open a [new clear and descriptive issue](../../issues/new).
   188в†’
   189в†’### Submitting pull requests
   191в†’Pull requests are the greatest contributions, so be sure they are focused in scope, and do avoid unrelated commits.
   192в†’
   193в†’-   Fork it!
   194в†’-   Clone your fork: `git clone https://github.com/<your-username>/mitt`
   195в†’-   Navigate to the newly cloned directory: `cd mitt`
   196в†’-   Create a new branch for the new feature: `git checkout -b my-new-feature`
   197в†’-   Install the tools necessary for development: `npm install`
   198в†’-   Make your changes.
   199в†’-   Commit your changes: `git commit -am 'Add some feature'`
   200в†’-   Push to the branch: `git push origin my-new-feature`
   201в†’-   Submit a pull request with full remarks documenting your changes.
   202в†’
